      <div type="text">
        <p style="heading4">Prologue, Paragraph 2</p>
        <note type="tnote" n="1"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">Alle</hi>. The first word
          of the Prologue and of each chapter in F begins with a rubricated initial letter, in blue
          ink with red flourishes. B features more elaborate rubrication on its first page for the
          Prologue and Chapter 1, with gilded initial letters and red and blue illuminations around
          the borders of the text but afterward uses a more basic rubrication similar to F, with
          initial letters in blue and red.</note>
        <p style="heading4">Prologue, Paragraph 8</p>
        <note type="tnote" n="2"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">this</hi>. So F. B adds:
            <hi rend="italic">Heer endiþ þe prologe and biginniþ þ</hi><hi rend="italic">e
            Apocalips</hi>.</note>
        <p style="heading4">Chapter 1, Paragraph 1</p>
        <note type="tnote" n="3"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">Apocalips</hi>. F marginal
          note: <hi rend="italic">þat is, revelacion eþer schewing</hi>.</note>
        <p style="heading4">Chapter 1, Paragraph 3</p>
        <note type="tnote" n="4"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">prickiden</hi>. F marginal
          note: <hi rend="italic">eþer crucifieden</hi>.</note>
        <note type="tnote" n="5"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">kinredis</hi>. F marginal
          note: <hi rend="italic">eþer lynagis</hi>.</note>
        <p style="heading4">Chapter 1, Paragraph 6</p>
        <note type="tnote" n="6"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">garnement</hi>. F marginal
          note: <hi rend="italic">eþer an awbe</hi> [white robe].</note>
        <note type="tnote" n="7"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">latoun</hi>. F marginal
          note: <hi rend="italic">eþer dross of gold</hi>.</note>
        <p style="heading4">Chapter 3, Paragraph 3</p>
        <note type="tnote" n="8"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">that thei ben</hi>. So B.
          F: <hi rend="italic">þei ben þat</hi>.</note>
        <p style="heading4">Chapter 3, Paragraph 5</p>
        <note type="tnote" n="9"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">collerie</hi>. F marginal
          note: <hi rend="italic">þat is, a medicyn for iȝen gederide of dyverse eerbis</hi>.</note>
        <p style="heading4">Chapter 4, Paragraph 1</p>
        <note type="tnote" n="10"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">dore</hi>. F marginal
          note: <hi rend="italic">þat is, þe undirstonding of scripturis</hi>.</note>
        <p style="heading4">Chapter 4, Paragraph 2</p>
        <note type="tnote" n="11"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">middil of the seete</hi>.
          So F. B adds: <hi rend="italic">and in þe cumpas of þe seete</hi>.</note>
        <p style="heading4">Chapter 6, Paragraph 1</p>
        <note type="tnote" n="12"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">whiyt hors</hi>. F
          marginal note: <hi rend="italic">þat is, holi chirche maad feir with baptem</hi>.</note>
        <p style="heading4">Chapter 6, Paragraph 2</p>
        <note type="tnote" n="13"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">reed hors</hi>. F
          marginal note: <hi rend="italic">þat is, opene pursuers</hi>.</note>
        <p style="heading4">Chapter 6, Paragraph 3</p>
        <note type="tnote" n="14"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">blac hors</hi>. F
          marginal note: <hi rend="italic">þat is, hiding hise vicis to sum men wiþ goode
            werkis</hi>.</note>
        <p style="heading4">Chapter 6, Paragraph 4</p>
        <note type="tnote" n="15"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">pale hors</hi>. F
          marginal note: <hi rend="italic">þat is, ipocritis shewing hem holie to þe peple þouȝ þei
            be not</hi>.</note>
        <note type="tnote" n="16"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">helle</hi>. F marginal
          note: <hi rend="italic">þ</hi><hi rend="italic">at is, men þat never ben fulle of worldli
            goodis</hi>.</note>
        <p style="heading4">Chapter 7, Paragraph 1</p>
        <note type="tnote" n="17"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">fourty</hi>. So B. F: <hi
            rend="italic">twenti</hi>.</note>
        <p style="heading4">Chapter 9, Paragraph 6</p>
        <note type="tnote" n="18"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">weren slayne</hi>. So F
          and B. This phrase is not in the Vulgate and appears to be clarifying that this group of
          evildoers did not die in the plagues.</note>
        <p style="heading4">Chapter 11, Paragraph 1</p>
        <note type="tnote" n="19"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">reud</hi>. F marginal
          note: <hi rend="italic">e</hi><hi rend="italic">þer mesure</hi>.</note>
        <note type="tnote" n="20"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">twei</hi>. F marginal
          note: <hi rend="italic">þat is, Enok and Elye</hi>.</note>
        <p style="heading4">Chapter 12, Paragraph 1</p>
        <note type="tnote" n="21"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">And the temple . . .
            greet hail</hi>. F marks the beginning of Chapter 12 here; modern convention assigns
          this first verse to the end of Chapter 11.</note>
        <p style="heading4">Chapter 12, Paragraph 5</p>
        <note type="tnote" n="22"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">maundementis</hi>. So B.
          F: <hi rend="italic">maundement</hi>.</note>
        <p style="heading4">Chapter 12, Paragraph 6</p>
        <note type="tnote" n="23"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">And he stood . . . the
            see</hi>. F places this sentence at the end of Chapter 12, following the Vulgate; the
          Authorized Version and most modern versions of the Bible assign it to the first half of
          13:1.</note>
        <p style="heading4">Chapter 18, Paragraph 4</p>
        <note type="tnote" n="24"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">amonye</hi>. F marginal
          note: <hi rend="italic">þat is, a swete tree</hi>.</note>
        <p style="heading4">Chapter 18, Paragraph 5</p>
        <note type="tnote" n="25"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">destitute</hi>. F
          marginal note: <hi rend="italic">eþer forsaken</hi>.</note>
        <p style="heading4">Chapter 18, Paragraph 6</p>
        <note type="tnote" n="26"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">the brennyng of it</hi>.
          So B. F: <hi rend="italic">brennyng þe of it</hi>.</note>
        <p style="heading4">Chapter 18, Paragraph 7</p>
        <note type="tnote" n="27"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">wiycchecraftis</hi>. F
          marginal note: <hi rend="italic">eþer venemyngis</hi>.</note>
        <p style="heading4">Chapter 20, Paragraph 3</p>
        <note type="tnote" n="28"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">of God</hi>. So B. F: <hi
            rend="italic">God of</hi>.</note>
        <p style="heading4">Chapter 22, Paragraph 5</p>
        <note type="tnote" n="29"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">houndis</hi>. F marginal
          note: <hi rend="italic">þat is, false prechours</hi>.</note>
        <note type="tnote" n="30"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">wiycchis</hi>. F marginal
          note: <hi rend="italic">eþer venemers</hi>.</note>
        <p style="heading4">Chapter 22, Paragraph 11</p>
        <note type="tnote" n="31"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">Apocalips</hi>. So F. B
          adds: <hi rend="italic">þat Joon wroot in þe ile of Pathmos, þe whiche is þe ende of þe
            Newe Testament</hi>.</note>
        <p style="heading4">Chapter 22, Paragraph 12</p>
        <note type="tnote" n="32"><space rend="indent1"/><hi rend="italic">M.CCCC</hi>. F: <hi
            rend="italic">M.CCC</hi>, followed by an erasure; the intended date is apparently 1408.
          Elizabeth Solopova writes, “The date on fol. 385r may have been altered to avoid
          censorship, but, according to Watson (1984), examination under UV light suggests that the
          scribe first wrote ‘M.ccc’ and the ‘and’ symbol, erased the latter, wrote it in the right
          place, and then forgot to insert the fourth ‘c’” (Solopova, <hi rend="italic">Manuscripts
            of the Wycliffite Bible</hi>, p. 146).</note>
